"# Chapter 9 — Transformer architecture

The transformer is the neural network architecture underneath
every modern large language model. Introduced by Google
researchers in June 2017 in the paper *Attention Is All You
Need* (Vaswani et al., arxiv 1706.03762).

Every LLM you have used is a transformer. GPT is a transformer.
Claude is a transformer. Llama is a transformer. Gemini is a
transformer. Mistral, DeepSeek, Grok — all transformers.

## What it is

Before 2017, sequence models were mostly recurrent — RNNs and
LSTMs — that processed one token at a time and carried a hidden
state forward. Attention had been used before, but as an add-on
to recurrent models.

Vaswani et al. proposed dropping the recurrence entirely.
Attention on its own was enough.

The core operation is called scaled dot-product attention. For
each token in a sequence, the model produces three vectors: a
query, a key, and a value. The token's output is a weighted sum
of value vectors from all the tokens, where the weights come
from the dot products between this token's query and every
other token's key.

That is the whole idea. Every token can look at every other
token in one step. No recurrence. No hidden state to pass
forward.

## Multi-head attention

One attention operation gives you one way of relating tokens.
The paper uses several attention heads in parallel — each with
its own learned query, key, and value projections — so the
model can attend to different kinds of relationships at once.

The outputs of all the heads are concatenated and projected
back into the same size as the input.

## Positional encoding

Because attention is order-independent by default, the paper
adds a positional encoding to each token's embedding so the
model can tell position 3 from position 17. The original paper
used a sinusoidal pattern with different frequencies at
different embedding dimensions.

Later models use different positional-encoding schemes — learned
positional embeddings, rotary position embeddings (RoPE),
ALiBi. The core idea is the same. Add position information into
the token representation somehow.

## The block

A transformer block stacks:

- Multi-head self-attention
- Add and norm (residual connection plus layer normalization)
- Feed-forward network (two linear layers with a non-linearity
  in between)
- Add and norm

Modern LLMs stack many of these blocks — dozens to hundreds. The
depth is where the reasoning capacity comes from.

## Encoder-decoder vs decoder-only

The original 2017 paper described an encoder-decoder transformer
for machine translation. The encoder read the source sentence
and produced representations. The decoder generated the target
sentence one token at a time, attending both to its own previous
tokens (with causal masking) and to the encoder outputs (with
cross-attention).

GPT and most modern chat LLMs use a decoder-only variant. Just
the causal-attention stack. Generate the next token given the
previous tokens. The 2017 encoder-decoder shape lives on in
translation and other sequence-to-sequence tasks.

## Why it worked

Two reasons that mattered.

First, transformers parallelize well on GPUs because there is no
sequential dependency across the sequence — you can compute
attention for every token position at once. RNNs cannot. This
made much larger models trainable in reasonable time.

Second, attention gave the model a way to relate distant tokens
directly. RNNs had trouble with long-range dependencies. The
transformer just looks.

Combine parallel training with long-range capability and you get
a shape that scales. The models could get bigger. The training
data could get bigger. Performance kept improving with scale.
That is the story of the last eight years of AI.

## The Book of ML

If you want to build a transformer by hand in Motoi Scheme, the
Book of ML chapter 12 (attention) and chapter 13 (transformer
block) walk you through it. That book is where the mechanics
live in this repo. This card is the history.

## What Motoi says about the transformer

The transformer is the neural network architecture underneath
modern LLMs. It came out of Google in June 2017. The paper is
*Attention Is All You Need*, Vaswani et al., arxiv 1706.03762.
Every LLM you have used is a descendant of that paper.

## What Motoi does not say about the transformer

I do not say `the transformer is the best architecture` — that
is a ranking, and there is ongoing research on state-space
models, MoE variants, and other alternatives that may or may
not displace the transformer eventually. I do not say `the
transformer will always be the answer`. Nobody knows.

## Where to read it

*Attention Is All You Need*, Vaswani, Shazeer, Parmar,
Uszkoreit, Jones, Gomez, Kaiser, Polosukhin. Google Brain and
University of Toronto. NeurIPS 2017. Arxiv 1706.03762.

The paper is short (eight pages plus appendix) and well written.
If you read one AI paper in your life, read this one.

## Motoi's take

The transformer paper is the single most important engineering
document of the modern AI era. It is one architecture and it is
in every model shipping today. That is enormous compounding
influence out of a single publication. Same kind of compounding
Shannon's information theory paper produced in 1948. Read the
paper. Come back.")
